26	17	ai	I'll write a simple Python script that prints 'hello'. Since this is a straightforward task, I'll provide a basic implementation along with a slightly more robust version.\n\n## Approach\nThis is a simple task that requires using Python's built-in `print()` function to output the string 'hello' to the console.\n\n## Code\n\n**Basic version:**\n```python\n#!/usr/bin/env python3\n"""\nSimple script to print 'hello' to the console.\n"""\n\ndef main():\n    """Main function that prints the greeting."""\n    print('hello')\n\nif __name__ == "__main__":\n    main()\n```\n\n**Alternative one-liner version:**\n```python\n#!/usr/bin/env python3\nprint('hello')\n```\n\n## How to use\n\n1. Save the code to a file (e.g., `hello.py`)\n2. Run it from the command line:\n   ```bash\n   python hello.py\n   ```\n   or\n   ```bash\n   python3 hello.py\n   ```\n\n## Explanation\n\n- The shebang line (`#!/usr/bin/env python3`) allows the script to be executed directly on Unix-like systems\n- I wrapped the print statement in a `main()` function following Python best practices\n- The `if __name__ == "__main__":` guard ensures the code only runs when the script is executed directly, not when imported as a module\n- Added a docstring for documentation\n\nBoth versions will output:\n```\nhello\n```\n\nThe first version is more suitable for production code due to its structure and documentation, while the second is perfectly fine for simple scripts.	{}	2026-02-03 07:05:14.574354
