39	24	ai	I'll create a comprehensive Binary Search Tree class with insert and search methods, including proper error handling and documentation.\n\n## Approach\nI'll implement a BST with:\n- A Node class to represent individual tree nodes\n- Insert method that maintains BST property (left < parent < right)\n- Search method that efficiently finds values\n- Additional helper methods for completeness\n\n## Complete Code\n\n```python\nclass TreeNode:\n    """\n    Represents a single node in the binary search tree.\n    """\n    def __init__(self, value):\n        self.value = value\n        self.left = None\n        self.right = None\n\nclass BinarySearchTree:\n    """\n    A Binary Search Tree implementation with insert and search operations.\n    \n    The BST maintains the property that for any node:\n    - All values in the left subtree are less than the node's value\n    - All values in the right subtree are greater than the node's value\n    """\n    \n    def __init__(self):\n        """Initialize an empty binary search tree."""\n        self.root = None\n        self.size = 0\n    \n    def insert(self, value):\n        """\n        Insert a value into the binary search tree.\n        \n        Args:\n            value: The value to insert (must be comparable)\n            \n        Returns:\n            bool: True if insertion was successful, False if value already exists\n            \n        Time Complexity: O(log n) average, O(n) worst case\n        """\n        if not self._is_comparable(value):\n            raise TypeError(f"Value {value} must be comparable (int, float, str, etc.)")\n        \n        if self.root is None:\n            self.root = TreeNode(value)\n            self.size += 1\n            return True\n        \n        return self._insert_recursive(self.root, value)\n    \n    def _insert_recursive(self, node, value):\n        """\n        Recursive helper method for insertion.\n        \n        Args:\n            node: Current node being examined\n            value: Value to insert\n            \n        Returns:\n            bool: True if inserted, False if duplicate\n        """\n        if value == node.value:\n            # Duplicate values are not allowed in this implementation\n            return False\n        elif value < node.value:\n            if node.left is None:\n                node.left = TreeNode(value)\n                self.size += 1\n                return True\n            else:\n                return self._insert_recursive(node.left, value)\n        else:  # value > node.value\n            if node.right is None:\n                node.right = TreeNode(value)\n                self.size += 1\n                return True\n            else:\n                return self._insert_recursive(node.right, value)\n    \n    def search(self, value):\n        """\n        Search for a value in the binary search tree.\n        \n        Args:\n            value: The value to search for\n            \n        Returns:\n            bool: True if value exists in the tree, False otherwise\n            \n        Time Complexity: O(log n) average, O(n) worst case\n        """\n        if not self._is_comparable(value):\n            raise TypeError(f"Value {value} must be comparable")\n        \n        return self._search_recursive(self.root, value)\n    \n    def _search_recursive(self, node, value):\n        """\n        Recursive helper method for searching.\n        \n        Args:\n            node: Current node being examined\n            value: Value to search for\n            \n        Returns:\n            bool: True if found, False otherwise\n        """\n        if node is None:\n            return False\n        \n        if value == node.value:\n            return True\n        elif value < node.value:\n            return self._search_recursive(node.left, value)\n        else:\n            return self._search_recursive(node.right, value)\n    \n    def find_node(self, value):\n        """\n        Find and return the node containing the specified value.\n        \n        Args:\n            value: The value to find\n            \n        Returns:\n            TreeNode or None: The node containing the value, or None if not found\n        """\n        return self._find_node_recursive(self.root, value)\n    \n    def _find_node_recursive(self, node, value):\n        """Recursive helper to find a node."""\n        if node is None or value == node.value:\n            return node\n        elif value < node.value:\n            return self._find_node_recursive(node.left, value)\n        else:\n            return self._find_node_recursive(node.right, value)\n    \n    def is_empty(self):\n        """Check if the tree is empty."""\n        return self.root is None\n    \n    def get_size(self):\n        """Get the number of nodes in the tree."""\n        return self.size\n    \n    def _is_comparable(self, value):\n        """\n        Check if a value is comparable (can be used with <, >, ==).\n        \n        Args:\n            value: Value to check\n            \n        Returns:\n            bool: True if comparable, False otherwise\n        """\n        try:\n            # Test if the value can be compared\n            value < value\n            return True\n        except TypeError:\n            return False\n    \n    def inorder_traversal(self):\n        """\n        Perform inorder traversal of the tree.\n        \n        Returns:\n            list: Values in sorted order\n        """\n        result = []\n        self._inorder_recursive(self.root, result)\n        return result\n    \n    def _inorder_recursive(self, node, result):\n        """Recursive helper for inorder traversal."""\n        if node is not None:\n            self._inorder_recursive(node.left, result)\n            result.append(node.value)\n            self._inorder_recursive(node.right, result)\n    \n    def __str__(self):\n        """String representation of the tree (inorder traversal)."""\n        if self.is_empty():\n            return "Empty BST"\n        return f"BST: {self.inorder_traversal()}"\n    \n    def __len__(self):\n        """Return the size of the tree."""\n        return self.size\n```\n\n## How to Use\n\n```python\n# Create a new binary search tree\nbst = BinarySearchTree()\n\n# Insert values\nprint(bst.insert(50))    # True\nprint(bst.insert(30))    # True\nprint(bst.insert(70))    # True\nprint(bst.insert(20))    # True\nprint(bst.insert(40))    # True\nprint(bst.insert(60))    # True\nprint(bst.insert(80))    # True\nprint(bst.insert(50))    # False (duplicate)\n\n# Search for values\nprint(bst.search(40))    # True\nprint(bst.search(90))    # False\n\n# Get tree information\nprint(f"Tree size: {len(bst)}")           # Tree size: 7\nprint(f"Is empty: {bst.is_empty()}")      # Is empty: False\nprint(f"Sorted values: {bst.inorder_traversal()}")  # [20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80]\n\n# String representation\nprint(bst)  # BST: [20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70, 80]\n\n# Error handling example\ntry:\n    bst.insert([1, 2, 3])  # Will raise TypeError\nexcept TypeError as e:\n    print(f"Error: {e}")\n```\n\n## Key Features\n\n1. **Type Safety**: Validates that inserted values are comparable\n2. **Duplicate Handling**: Prevents duplicate values (returns False)\n3. **Efficient Operations**: O(log n) average time complexity for balanced trees\n4. **Additional Utilities**: Size tracking, traversal methods, string representation\n5. **Error Handling**: Proper exception handling for invalid inputs\n6. **Clean API**: Intuitive method names and comprehensive documentation\n\nThe implementation maintains the BST invariant and provides a solid foundation that can be extended with additional operations like deletion, tree balancing, or different traversal methods.	{}	2026-02-03 07:25:47.271071
