87	45	ai	I'll create a Python function to calculate Fibonacci numbers with multiple implementation approaches for different use cases.\n\n## Approach\n\nI'll provide three implementations:\n1. **Iterative** - Most efficient for general use\n2. **Memoized recursive** - Good balance of readability and performance\n3. **Generator** - Memory efficient for sequences\n\n## Complete Code\n\n```python\nfrom functools import lru_cache\nfrom typing import Generator, Union\n\ndef fibonacci_iterative(n: int) -> int:\n    """\n    Calculate the nth Fibonacci number using iterative approach.\n    \n    Most efficient method with O(n) time and O(1) space complexity.\n    \n    Args:\n        n (int): Position in Fibonacci sequence (0-indexed)\n        \n    Returns:\n        int: The nth Fibonacci number\n        \n    Raises:\n        ValueError: If n is negative\n        \n    Examples:\n        >>> fibonacci_iterative(0)\n        0\n        >>> fibonacci_iterative(10)\n        55\n    """\n    if n < 0:\n        raise ValueError("Fibonacci sequence is not defined for negative numbers")\n    \n    if n <= 1:\n        return n\n    \n    # Initialize first two Fibonacci numbers\n    prev, curr = 0, 1\n    \n    # Calculate iteratively up to nth number\n    for _ in range(2, n + 1):\n        prev, curr = curr, prev + curr\n    \n    return curr\n\n\n@lru_cache(maxsize=None)\ndef fibonacci_memoized(n: int) -> int:\n    """\n    Calculate the nth Fibonacci number using memoized recursion.\n    \n    Uses Python's LRU cache for automatic memoization.\n    Good for repeated calls with same values.\n    \n    Args:\n        n (int): Position in Fibonacci sequence (0-indexed)\n        \n    Returns:\n        int: The nth Fibonacci number\n        \n    Raises:\n        ValueError: If n is negative\n    """\n    if n < 0:\n        raise ValueError("Fibonacci sequence is not defined for negative numbers")\n    \n    if n <= 1:\n        return n\n    \n    return fibonacci_memoized(n - 1) + fibonacci_memoized(n - 2)\n\n\ndef fibonacci_generator(limit: int) -> Generator[int, None, None]:\n    """\n    Generate Fibonacci numbers up to the specified limit.\n    \n    Memory efficient generator that yields Fibonacci numbers one at a time.\n    \n    Args:\n        limit (int): Maximum number of Fibonacci numbers to generate\n        \n    Yields:\n        int: Next Fibonacci number in sequence\n        \n    Examples:\n        >>> list(fibonacci_generator(5))\n        [0, 1, 1, 2, 3]\n    """\n    if limit <= 0:\n        return\n    \n    a, b = 0, 1\n    count = 0\n    \n    while count < limit:\n        yield a\n        a, b = b, a + b\n        count += 1\n\n\ndef fibonacci_sequence(n: int) -> list[int]:\n    """\n    Generate a list of the first n Fibonacci numbers.\n    \n    Args:\n        n (int): Number of Fibonacci numbers to generate\n        \n    Returns:\n        list[int]: List containing first n Fibonacci numbers\n        \n    Examples:\n        >>> fibonacci_sequence(8)\n        [0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13]\n    """\n    return list(fibonacci_generator(n))\n\n\n# Example usage and testing\nif __name__ == "__main__":\n    # Test the functions\n    test_cases = [0, 1, 5, 10, 20]\n    \n    print("Fibonacci Number Calculations:")\n    print("-" * 40)\n    \n    for n in test_cases:\n        iterative_result = fibonacci_iterative(n)\n        memoized_result = fibonacci_memoized(n)\n        \n        print(f"F({n}) = {iterative_result}")\n        \n        # Verify both methods give same result\n        assert iterative_result == memoized_result, f"Mismatch at n={n}"\n    \n    print("\\nFirst 10 Fibonacci numbers:")\n    print(fibonacci_sequence(10))\n    \n    print("\\nUsing generator (first 8 numbers):")\n    for i, fib_num in enumerate(fibonacci_generator(8)):\n        print(f"F({i}) = {fib_num}")\n```\n\n## How to Use\n\n### Basic Usage:\n```python\n# Calculate single Fibonacci number\nresult = fibonacci_iterative(10)  # Returns 55\n\n# Get sequence of Fibonacci numbers\nsequence = fibonacci_sequence(8)  # Returns [0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13]\n\n# Use generator for memory efficiency\nfor fib_num in fibonacci_generator(5):\n    print(fib_num)  # Prints: 0, 1, 1, 2, 3\n```\n\n### Performance Characteristics:\n- **`fibonacci_iterative()`**: Best for single calculations, O(n) time, O(1) space\n- **`fibonacci_memoized()`**: Best when calling repeatedly with same values\n- **`fibonacci_generator()`**: Best for generating sequences without storing all values in memory\n\n### Error Handling:\nAll functions include proper input validation and raise `ValueError` for negative inputs, since Fibonacci numbers are typically defined for non-negative integers only.	{}	2026-02-03 07:33:02.267247
