99	51	ai	I'll create a Python function to calculate factorial with proper error handling and documentation.\n\n## Approach\nI'll provide two implementations:\n1. An iterative version (more memory efficient)\n2. A recursive version (more intuitive but with recursion limits)\n\nBoth will include input validation and clear documentation.\n\n## Complete Code\n\n```python\ndef factorial_iterative(n):\n    """\n    Calculate the factorial of a non-negative integer using iteration.\n    \n    Args:\n        n (int): A non-negative integer\n        \n    Returns:\n        int: The factorial of n (n!)\n        \n    Raises:\n        TypeError: If n is not an integer\n        ValueError: If n is negative\n        \n    Examples:\n        >>> factorial_iterative(5)\n        120\n        >>> factorial_iterative(0)\n        1\n    """\n    # Input validation\n    if not isinstance(n, int):\n        raise TypeError(f"Expected integer, got {type(n).__name__}")\n    \n    if n < 0:\n        raise ValueError("Factorial is not defined for negative numbers")\n    \n    # Handle base cases\n    if n == 0 or n == 1:\n        return 1\n    \n    # Calculate factorial iteratively\n    result = 1\n    for i in range(2, n + 1):\n        result *= i\n    \n    return result\n\n\ndef factorial_recursive(n):\n    """\n    Calculate the factorial of a non-negative integer using recursion.\n    \n    Args:\n        n (int): A non-negative integer\n        \n    Returns:\n        int: The factorial of n (n!)\n        \n    Raises:\n        TypeError: If n is not an integer\n        ValueError: If n is negative\n        RecursionError: If n is too large (typically > 1000)\n        \n    Examples:\n        >>> factorial_recursive(5)\n        120\n        >>> factorial_recursive(0)\n        1\n    """\n    # Input validation\n    if not isinstance(n, int):\n        raise TypeError(f"Expected integer, got {type(n).__name__}")\n    \n    if n < 0:\n        raise ValueError("Factorial is not defined for negative numbers")\n    \n    # Base cases\n    if n == 0 or n == 1:\n        return 1\n    \n    # Recursive case\n    return n * factorial_recursive(n - 1)\n\n\n# Alternative using math.factorial for comparison\nimport math\n\ndef factorial_builtin(n):\n    """\n    Calculate factorial using Python's built-in math.factorial function.\n    \n    Args:\n        n (int): A non-negative integer\n        \n    Returns:\n        int: The factorial of n (n!)\n        \n    Note:\n        This is the most efficient and robust implementation for production use.\n    """\n    if not isinstance(n, int):\n        raise TypeError(f"Expected integer, got {type(n).__name__}")\n    \n    return math.factorial(n)\n\n\n# Example usage and testing\nif __name__ == "__main__":\n    # Test cases\n    test_values = [0, 1, 5, 10]\n    \n    print("Factorial Calculations:")\n    print("-" * 40)\n    \n    for value in test_values:\n        iter_result = factorial_iterative(value)\n        rec_result = factorial_recursive(value)\n        builtin_result = factorial_builtin(value)\n        \n        print(f"{value}! = {iter_result}")\n        \n        # Verify all methods give same result\n        assert iter_result == rec_result == builtin_result\n    \n    # Error handling examples\n    print("\\nError Handling Examples:")\n    print("-" * 40)\n    \n    try:\n        factorial_iterative(-1)\n    except ValueError as e:\n        print(f"Negative input error: {e}")\n    \n    try:\n        factorial_iterative(3.14)\n    except TypeError as e:\n        print(f"Non-integer input error: {e}")\n```\n\n## How to Use\n\n1. **Basic usage:**\n```python\nresult = factorial_iterative(5)  # Returns 120\nprint(f"5! = {result}")\n```\n\n2. **For production code, I recommend the iterative version** as it:\n   - Doesn't hit recursion limits\n   - Uses constant memory\n   - Is generally faster for large numbers\n\n3. **For maximum performance and robustness, use `math.factorial()`** which is implemented in C and handles edge cases optimally.\n\n4. **Error handling is built-in** - the functions will raise appropriate exceptions for invalid inputs.\n\nThe iterative implementation is the best balance of readability, performance, and educational value while maintaining production-quality standards.	{}	2026-02-03 07:48:18.389725
