131	64	ai	Machine learning is a subset of artificial intelligence that enables computers to learn and make decisions from data without being explicitly programmed for every task.\n\n**Supervised Learning:**\nUses labeled training data where both input and correct output are provided. The algorithm learns to map inputs to outputs.\n\nExamples:\n- Email spam detection (input: email content, output: spam/not spam)\n- Image classification (input: photo, output: cat/dog/bird)\n- House price prediction (input: size, location, features, output: price)\n- Medical diagnosis (input: symptoms/test results, output: disease/healthy)\n\nCommon algorithms: Linear regression, decision trees, random forests, neural networks, support vector machines.\n\n**Unsupervised Learning:**\nFinds hidden patterns in data without labeled examples. The algorithm discovers structure in unlabeled data.\n\nExamples:\n- Customer segmentation (grouping customers by purchasing behavior)\n- Market basket analysis (finding products frequently bought together)\n- Anomaly detection (identifying unusual network traffic or fraudulent transactions)\n- Gene sequencing (finding patterns in DNA data)\n- Recommendation systems (suggesting products based on user similarity)\n\nCommon algorithms: K-means clustering, hierarchical clustering, principal component analysis (PCA), association rules.\n\n**Reinforcement Learning:**\nLearns through interaction with an environment, receiving rewards or penalties for actions. The agent learns optimal behavior through trial and error.\n\nExamples:\n- Game playing (AlphaGo, chess engines)\n- Autonomous vehicles (learning to navigate traffic)\n- Robot control (learning to walk or manipulate objects)\n- Trading algorithms (learning optimal buy/sell strategies)\n- Chatbots (learning to provide better responses based on user feedback)\n\nKey concepts: Agent, environment, actions, rewards, policy. Common algorithms: Q-learning, policy gradients, actor-critic methods.\n\nEach type serves different purposes: supervised for prediction with known outcomes, unsupervised for discovering hidden patterns, and reinforcement for learning optimal behavior through experience.	{}	2026-02-03 07:50:31.895499
