259	118	ai	**Microservices vs Monolithic Architecture:**\n\n**Monolithic Architecture:**\n- Single deployable unit where all components are interconnected\n- All features built into one large application\n- Shared database and runtime\n- Simple to develop, test, and deploy initially\n- Easier debugging and monitoring\n- Can become complex and hard to maintain as it grows\n- Scaling requires scaling the entire application\n\n**Microservices Architecture:**\n- Application broken into small, independent services\n- Each service handles a specific business function\n- Services communicate via APIs (REST, messaging)\n- Independent deployment and scaling\n- Technology diversity - different services can use different tech stacks\n- Better fault isolation - one service failure doesn't crash everything\n- More complex to manage (networking, monitoring, data consistency)\n- Requires DevOps maturity\n\n**When to choose:**\n- **Monolithic**: Small teams, simple applications, rapid prototyping, limited DevOps experience\n- **Microservices**: Large teams, complex domains, need for independent scaling, mature DevOps practices\n\nMany successful companies start monolithic and evolve to microservices as they grow.	{}	2026-02-03 10:01:54.689449
260	119	human	What is Docker and how does containerization work?	{}	2026-02-03 10:01:55.216713
261	119	ai	Docker is a containerization platform that allows you to package applications and their dependencies into lightweight, portable containers. Here's how containerization works:\n\n**What is Docker:**\n- Docker is a platform that uses OS-level virtualization to deliver software in packages called containers\n- It provides a consistent environment for applications to run across different systems\n- Docker uses a client-server architecture with Docker Engine as the runtime\n\n**How Containerization Works:**\n1. **Images**: Docker creates read-only templates (images) that contain the application code, runtime, libraries, and dependencies\n2. **Containers**: Running instances of images that are isolated from the host system and other containers\n3. **Layered File System**: Images are built in layers, allowing for efficient storage and sharing of common components\n4. **Namespace Isolation**: Containers have their own process space, network interfaces, and file systems\n5. **Resource Control**: Uses cgroups to limit CPU, memory, and other resources\n\n**Key Benefits:**\n- Consistency across development, testing, and production environments\n- Faster deployment and scaling\n- Resource efficiency compared to traditional VMs\n- Easy application portability\n- Simplified dependency management\n\n**Common Use Cases:**\n- Microservices architecture\n- CI/CD pipelines\n- Application modernization\n- Development environment standardization	{}	2026-02-03 10:02:18.301478
262	120	human	Describe the CAP theorem in distributed systems	{}	2026-02-03 10:02:18.830764
263	120	ai	The CAP theorem, also known as Brewer's theorem, is a fundamental principle in distributed systems that states you can only guarantee two out of three properties simultaneously:\n\n**C - Consistency**: All nodes see the same data at the same time. Every read receives the most recent write or an error.\n\n**A - Availability**: The system remains operational and responsive, meaning every request receives a response (success or failure).\n\n**P - Partition Tolerance**: The system continues to operate despite network failures or communication breakdowns between nodes.\n\nThe theorem implies that in the presence of a network partition (which is inevitable in distributed systems), you must choose between consistency and availability:\n\n- **CP Systems** (Consistency + Partition Tolerance): Sacrifice availability during partitions. Examples: MongoDB, Redis Cluster, HBase\n- **AP Systems** (Availability + Partition Tolerance): Sacrifice consistency, allowing eventual consistency. Examples: Cassandra, DynamoDB, CouchDB\n- **CA Systems** (Consistency + Availability): Only possible when there are no network partitions, essentially single-node systems or systems that can't handle partitions\n\nIn practice, most modern distributed systems are designed as either CP or AP, with many favoring eventual consistency (AP) for better user experience.	{}	2026-02-03 10:02:40.903958
264	121	human	What are the best practices for REST API design?	{}	2026-02-03 10:02:41.436406
265	121	ai	Here are the key best practices for REST API design:\n\n**1. Use HTTP Methods Correctly**\n- GET: Retrieve data (idempotent)\n- POST: Create new resources\n- PUT: Update/replace entire resource (idempotent)\n- PATCH: Partial updates\n- DELETE: Remove resources (idempotent)\n\n**2. Design Clear Resource URLs**\n- Use nouns, not verbs: `/users` not `/getUsers`\n- Use plural nouns: `/users/123` not `/user/123`\n- Hierarchical structure: `/users/123/orders/456`\n- Keep URLs simple and predictable\n\n**3. Use Proper HTTP Status Codes**\n- 200: Success\n- 201: Created\n- 400: Bad Request\n- 401: Unauthorized\n- 404: Not Found\n- 500: Internal Server Error\n\n**4. Implement Consistent Response Format**\n- Use JSON as default format\n- Include metadata (pagination, timestamps)\n- Consistent error response structure\n\n**5. Version Your API**\n- URL versioning: `/api/v1/users`\n- Header versioning: `Accept: application/vnd.api+json;version=1`\n\n**6. Security Best Practices**\n- Use HTTPS\n- Implement authentication (JWT, OAuth)\n- Rate limiting\n- Input validation\n\n**7. Documentation & Testing**\n- Comprehensive API documentation\n- Include examples\n- Automated testing\n- Interactive documentation (Swagger/OpenAPI)	{}	2026-02-03 10:03:02.56604
266	122	human	Explain OAuth 2.0 authentication flow	{}	2026-02-03 10:03:03.093106
267	122	ai	OAuth 2.0 is an authorization framework that enables applications to obtain limited access to user accounts. Here's the basic flow:\n\n1. **Authorization Request**: The client application redirects the user to the authorization server with parameters like client_id, redirect_uri, response_type, and scope.\n\n2. **User Authorization**: The user authenticates with the authorization server and grants or denies the application's request for access.\n\n3. **Authorization Grant**: If approved, the authorization server redirects back to the client with an authorization code (in authorization code flow) or access token (in implicit flow).\n\n4. **Access Token Request**: The client exchanges the authorization code for an access token by making a POST request to the token endpoint with the code, client credentials, and redirect_uri.\n\n5. **Access Token Response**: The authorization server validates the request and returns an access token (and optionally a refresh token).\n\n6. **Protected Resource Access**: The client uses the access token to make authenticated requests to the resource server by including it in the Authorization header.\n\nCommon grant types include Authorization Code (most secure), Implicit (for SPAs), Client Credentials (server-to-server), and Resource Owner Password Credentials (legacy).	{}	2026-02-03 10:03:24.320034
