269	123	ai	GraphQL is a query language and runtime for APIs that allows clients to request exactly the data they need. Unlike REST APIs that have fixed endpoints returning predetermined data structures, GraphQL provides a single endpoint where clients can specify precisely what fields and relationships they want.\n\nKey advantages of GraphQL:\n- **Precise data fetching**: Request only the fields you need, reducing over-fetching\n- **Single request**: Fetch related data in one query instead of multiple REST calls\n- **Strong type system**: Self-documenting with built-in schema introspection\n- **Real-time subscriptions**: Built-in support for live data updates\n- **Backward compatibility**: Add fields without versioning\n\nUse GraphQL over REST when:\n- You have complex, nested data relationships\n- Mobile apps need to minimize data transfer\n- Frontend teams need flexibility in data fetching\n- You want to avoid multiple API calls (N+1 problem)\n- Real-time features are important\n- You have diverse clients with different data needs\n\nStick with REST when:\n- Simple CRUD operations are sufficient\n- Caching is critical (HTTP caching works well with REST)\n- File uploads/downloads are primary use cases\n- Team lacks GraphQL expertise\n- Existing REST infrastructure works well	{}	2026-02-03 10:03:44.819523
270	124	human	Describe the differences between SQL and NoSQL databases	{}	2026-02-03 10:03:45.350645
271	124	ai	SQL and NoSQL databases differ in several key ways:\n\n**SQL Databases (Relational):**\n- Use structured query language (SQL) for data manipulation\n- Follow ACID properties (Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability)\n- Have predefined schemas with tables, rows, and columns\n- Support complex joins and relationships between tables\n- Vertically scalable (scale up by adding more power to existing hardware)\n- Examples: MySQL, PostgreSQL, Oracle, SQL Server\n- Best for: Complex queries, transactions, data integrity requirements\n\n**NoSQL Databases (Non-relational):**\n- Use various query languages or APIs (not SQL)\n- Often sacrifice some ACID properties for performance and scalability\n- Schema-flexible or schema-less design\n- Four main types: Document, Key-Value, Column-family, Graph\n- Horizontally scalable (scale out by adding more servers)\n- Examples: MongoDB, Redis, Cassandra, Neo4j\n- Best for: Large-scale applications, rapid development, unstructured data\n\n**When to choose:**\n- SQL: When you need complex relationships, transactions, and data consistency\n- NoSQL: When you need high scalability, flexibility, or are working with unstructured data	{}	2026-02-03 10:04:07.05458
272	125	human	What is Kubernetes and why is it important?	{}	2026-02-03 10:04:07.58649
273	125	ai	Kubernetes is an open-source container orchestration platform that automates the deployment, scaling, and management of containerized applications. Originally developed by Google, it's now maintained by the Cloud Native Computing Foundation.\n\nKubernetes is important because it:\n\n1. **Automates container management**: Handles deployment, scaling, and operations of application containers across clusters of hosts\n\n2. **Provides high availability**: Automatically restarts failed containers, replaces containers, and kills containers that don't respond to health checks\n\n3. **Enables scalability**: Can automatically scale applications up or down based on CPU usage or other metrics\n\n4. **Offers service discovery and load balancing**: Automatically distributes network traffic to maintain stable deployments\n\n5. **Supports rolling updates**: Allows you to update applications without downtime by gradually replacing old versions\n\n6. **Manages storage**: Automatically mounts storage systems of your choice (local, cloud providers, network storage)\n\n7. **Provides resource optimization**: Efficiently packs containers onto nodes to make the best use of resources\n\n8. **Enables portability**: Works across different cloud providers and on-premises environments, avoiding vendor lock-in\n\nKubernetes has become the de facto standard for container orchestration in modern cloud-native applications, making it essential for organizations adopting microservices architectures and DevOps practices.	{}	2026-02-03 10:04:29.54223
274	126	human	Explain the concept of CI/CD pipelines	{}	2026-02-03 10:04:30.068126
275	126	ai	CI/CD (Continuous Integration/Continuous Deployment) pipelines are automated workflows that help development teams integrate code changes frequently and deploy applications reliably.\n\n**Continuous Integration (CI):**\n- Developers frequently merge code changes into a shared repository\n- Automated builds and tests run on every code commit\n- Catches integration issues early and ensures code quality\n- Common tools: Jenkins, GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, CircleCI\n\n**Continuous Deployment/Delivery (CD):**\n- **Continuous Delivery**: Code is automatically prepared for release but requires manual approval for production\n- **Continuous Deployment**: Code automatically deploys to production after passing all tests\n- Reduces manual errors and speeds up release cycles\n\n**Typical Pipeline Stages:**\n1. **Source**: Code commit triggers the pipeline\n2. **Build**: Compile code and create artifacts\n3. **Test**: Run unit tests, integration tests, security scans\n4. **Deploy to Staging**: Deploy to test environment\n5. **Production Deploy**: Release to live environment\n6. **Monitor**: Track application performance and health\n\n**Benefits:**\n- Faster time to market\n- Reduced deployment risks\n- Improved code quality\n- Better collaboration between teams\n- Quick rollback capabilities\n\n**Key Practices:**\n- Automated testing at every stage\n- Infrastructure as Code (IaC)\n- Feature flags for safe releases\n- Monitoring and alerting\n- Version control for all changes	{}	2026-02-03 10:04:52.812107
276	127	human	What are design patterns and name 3 common ones?	{}	2026-02-03 10:04:53.343306
277	127	ai	Design patterns are reusable solutions to commonly occurring problems in software design. They represent best practices and proven approaches that developers can apply to solve recurring design challenges in object-oriented programming.\n\nThree common design patterns are:\n\n1. **Singleton Pattern** - Ensures a class has only one instance and provides global access to it. Useful for database connections, logging, or configuration settings.\n\n2. **Observer Pattern** - Defines a one-to-many dependency between objects so that when one object changes state, all dependent objects are notified automatically. Common in event handling systems and MVC architectures.\n\n3. **Factory Pattern** - Creates objects without specifying their exact classes, providing an interface for creating families of related objects. Useful when you need to create objects based on certain conditions or parameters.	{}	2026-02-03 10:05:12.557069
