289	133	ai	A message queue is a communication mechanism that allows applications to send and receive messages asynchronously. It acts as a buffer between message producers (senders) and consumers (receivers), storing messages until they can be processed.\n\nKey characteristics:\n- **Asynchronous communication**: Producers don't need to wait for consumers to process messages\n- **Decoupling**: Applications don't need to know about each other directly\n- **Reliability**: Messages are persisted until successfully processed\n- **Scalability**: Multiple producers and consumers can work independently\n\nWhen to use message queues:\n\n1. **Microservices communication**: Enable loose coupling between services\n2. **Load balancing**: Distribute work across multiple workers\n3. **Handling traffic spikes**: Buffer requests during high load periods\n4. **Background processing**: Offload time-consuming tasks (email sending, image processing)\n5. **Event-driven architectures**: Trigger actions based on events\n6. **System integration**: Connect different systems or technologies\n7. **Fault tolerance**: Ensure messages aren't lost if a service goes down\n\nPopular message queue systems include RabbitMQ, Apache Kafka, Amazon SQS, Redis, and Apache ActiveMQ.	{}	2026-02-03 10:07:14.158182
