303	140	ai	I'll create a function that efficiently merges two sorted lists using a two-pointer approach.\n\n## Approach\nI'll use two pointers to traverse both lists simultaneously, comparing elements and adding the smaller one to the result. This maintains the sorted order while achieving O(n + m) time complexity.\n\n## Code\n\n```python\ndef merge_sorted_lists(list1, list2):\n    """\n    Merges two sorted lists into a single sorted list.\n    \n    Args:\n        list1 (list): First sorted list (ascending order)\n        list2 (list): Second sorted list (ascending order)\n    \n    Returns:\n        list: A new sorted list containing all elements from both input lists\n    \n    Time Complexity: O(n + m) where n and m are lengths of the input lists\n    Space Complexity: O(n + m) for the result list\n    \n    Example:\n        >>> merge_sorted_lists([1, 3, 5], [2, 4, 6])\n        [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]\n    """\n    # Handle edge cases\n    if not list1:\n        return list2.copy() if list2 else []\n    if not list2:\n        return list1.copy()\n    \n    # Initialize pointers and result list\n    i, j = 0, 0\n    merged = []\n    \n    # Compare elements and merge while both lists have remaining elements\n    while i < len(list1) and j < len(list2):\n        if list1[i] <= list2[j]:\n            merged.append(list1[i])\n            i += 1\n        else:\n            merged.append(list2[j])\n            j += 1\n    \n    # Add remaining elements from list1 (if any)\n    while i < len(list1):\n        merged.append(list1[i])\n        i += 1\n    \n    # Add remaining elements from list2 (if any)\n    while j < len(list2):\n        merged.append(list2[j])\n        j += 1\n    \n    return merged\n\n\n# Example usage and test cases\nif __name__ == "__main__":\n    # Test cases\n    test_cases = [\n        ([1, 3, 5], [2, 4, 6]),           # Normal case\n        ([1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]),           # No overlap\n        ([1, 1, 2], [1, 3, 3]),           # Duplicates\n        ([], [1, 2, 3]),                  # Empty first list\n        ([1, 2, 3], []),                  # Empty second list\n        ([], []),                         # Both empty\n        ([5], [1, 2, 3, 4]),             # Single element\n    ]\n    \n    for i, (list1, list2) in enumerate(test_cases, 1):\n        result = merge_sorted_lists(list1, list2)\n        print(f"Test {i}: merge_sorted_lists({list1}, {list2}) = {result}")\n```\n\n## How to Use\n\n```python\n# Basic usage\nlist_a = [1, 3, 5, 7]\nlist_b = [2, 4, 6, 8]\nmerged = merge_sorted_lists(list_a, list_b)\nprint(merged)  # Output: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8]\n\n# Works with any comparable data types\nnames1 = ["Alice", "Charlie"]\nnames2 = ["Bob", "David"]\nmerged_names = merge_sorted_lists(names1, names2)\nprint(merged_names)  # Output: ['Alice', 'Bob', 'Charlie', 'David']\n```\n\n## Key Features\n\n- **Efficient**: O(n + m) time complexity, single pass through both lists\n- **Memory safe**: Creates a new list without modifying inputs\n- **Robust error handling**: Handles empty lists and edge cases\n- **Maintains stability**: Equal elements preserve their relative order\n- **Type flexible**: Works with any comparable data types (numbers, strings, etc.)\n\nThe function assumes both input lists are already sorted in ascending order. If you need to handle unsorted inputs, you would need to sort them first using `sorted()`.	{}	2026-02-03 10:12:12.331607
