311	144	ai	I'll create a robust palindrome checker that handles various edge cases and follows Python best practices.\n\n## Approach\nI'll implement a function that:\n- Normalizes the input by removing non-alphanumeric characters and converting to lowercase\n- Uses two-pointer technique for efficient comparison\n- Includes comprehensive error handling and documentation\n\n## Code\n\n```python\nimport re\nfrom typing import Union\n\n\ndef is_palindrome(text: Union[str, None], ignore_case: bool = True, \n                  alphanumeric_only: bool = True) -> bool:\n    """\n    Check if a string is a palindrome.\n    \n    A palindrome reads the same forwards and backwards. This function can\n    optionally ignore case and non-alphanumeric characters.\n    \n    Args:\n        text (str | None): The string to check for palindrome property\n        ignore_case (bool): If True, ignore case differences (default: True)\n        alphanumeric_only (bool): If True, only consider alphanumeric characters \n                                 (default: True)\n    \n    Returns:\n        bool: True if the string is a palindrome, False otherwise\n        \n    Raises:\n        TypeError: If text is not a string or None\n        \n    Examples:\n        >>> is_palindrome("racecar")\n        True\n        >>> is_palindrome("A man, a plan, a canal: Panama")\n        True\n        >>> is_palindrome("race a car")\n        False\n        >>> is_palindrome("Madam", ignore_case=False)\n        False\n        >>> is_palindrome("")\n        True\n        >>> is_palindrome(None)\n        False\n    """\n    # Handle None input\n    if text is None:\n        return False\n    \n    # Type validation\n    if not isinstance(text, str):\n        raise TypeError(f"Expected string or None, got {type(text).__name__}")\n    \n    # Handle empty string (considered a palindrome)\n    if not text:\n        return True\n    \n    # Normalize the string based on options\n    processed_text = text\n    \n    if alphanumeric_only:\n        # Remove non-alphanumeric characters\n        processed_text = re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z0-9]', '', processed_text)\n    \n    if ignore_case:\n        processed_text = processed_text.lower()\n    \n    # Handle edge case where processed string becomes empty\n    if not processed_text:\n        return True\n    \n    # Two-pointer approach for efficient comparison\n    left = 0\n    right = len(processed_text) - 1\n    \n    while left < right:\n        if processed_text[left] != processed_text[right]:\n            return False\n        left += 1\n        right -= 1\n    \n    return True\n\n\ndef is_palindrome_simple(text: Union[str, None]) -> bool:\n    """\n    Simple palindrome checker with minimal preprocessing.\n    \n    Only performs case-insensitive comparison without removing special characters.\n    Useful when you want to preserve the original string structure.\n    \n    Args:\n        text (str | None): The string to check\n        \n    Returns:\n        bool: True if palindrome, False otherwise\n        \n    Examples:\n        >>> is_palindrome_simple("Madam")\n        True\n        >>> is_palindrome_simple("A man, a plan, a canal: Panama")\n        False\n    """\n    if text is None:\n        return False\n    \n    if not isinstance(text, str):\n        raise TypeError(f"Expected string or None, got {type(text).__name__}")\n    \n    normalized = text.lower()\n    return normalized == normalized[::-1]\n\n\n# Example usage and testing\nif __name__ == "__main__":\n    # Test cases\n    test_cases = [\n        ("racecar", True),\n        ("A man, a plan, a canal: Panama", True),\n        ("race a car", False),\n        ("", True),\n        ("a", True),\n        ("Madam", True),\n        ("12321", True),\n        ("hello", False),\n        ("Was it a car or a cat I saw?", True),\n    ]\n    \n    print("Testing is_palindrome function:")\n    print("-" * 40)\n    \n    for text, expected in test_cases:\n        result = is_palindrome(text)\n        status = "✓" if result == expected else "✗"\n        print(f"{status} '{text}' -> {result} (expected: {expected})")\n    \n    # Test edge cases\n    print("\\nTesting edge cases:")\n    print("-" * 20)\n    \n    try:\n        print(f"None input: {is_palindrome(None)}")\n        print(f"Empty string: {is_palindrome('')}")\n        print(f"Single char: {is_palindrome('a')}")\n        print(f"Case sensitive: {is_palindrome('Aa', ignore_case=False)}")\n        print(f"With special chars: {is_palindrome('A!a', alphanumeric_only=False)}")\n    except Exception as e:\n        print(f"Error: {e}")\n```\n\n## How to Use\n\n1. **Basic usage**: `is_palindrome("racecar")` returns `True`\n\n2. **With options**:\n   - `is_palindrome("Madam", ignore_case=False)` - case-sensitive check\n   - `is_palindrome("A!a", alphanumeric_only=False)` - include special characters\n\n3. **Simple version**: Use `is_palindrome_simple()` for basic case-insensitive checking without character filtering\n\n## Key Features\n\n- **Type safety**: Uses type hints and validates input types\n- **Flexible options**: Control case sensitivity and character filtering\n- **Efficient algorithm**: O(n) time complexity with two-pointer technique\n- **Comprehensive error handling**: Graceful handling of None and invalid inputs\n- **Well-documented**: Clear docstrings with examples\n- **Production-ready**: Includes edge case handling and proper validation\n\nThe function handles common real-world scenarios like punctuation, spaces, and mixed case while maintaining clean, readable code structure.	{}	2026-02-03 10:15:53.91245
